2021}}<ref name=\":02\" />\n|-\n|174\n|{{flag|Saint Kitts and Nevis}}\n|{{dts|22 March 2021}}<ref name=\":02\" />\n|-\n|175\n|{{flag|Timor-Leste}}\n|{{dts|4 May 2022}}<ref name=\":02\" />\n|-\n|176\n|{{flag|Guinea-Bissau}}\n|{{Dts|6 December 2023}}<ref>{{Cite web |date=6 December 2023 |title=LE PR√âSIDENT DE LA R√âPUBLIQUE A RE√áU LES CR√âANCES DES NOUVEAUX AMBASSADEURS |url=https://www.facebook.com/galumse/posts/pfbid0rVo3jYty7pMdq2JE6kRDztq6ithfBz9t4tCi85fXjAGMTcRRD527SNVpH8ihZz8El |access-date=3 March 2024 |website=[[Facebook]] |language=fr}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=7 December 2023 |title=Diplomatic cooperation, solidarity between SL ‚Äì Guinea-Bissau strengthened |url=https://www.dailynews.lk/2023/12/07/local/277120/diplomatic-cooperation-solidarity-between-sl-guinea-bissau-strengthened |access-date=26 October 2025 |work=[[Daily News (Sri Lanka)]]}}</ref>\n|-\n|177\n|{{flag|Antigua and Barbuda}}\n|{{dts|3 October 2025}}<ref name=\":02\" />\n|-\n|178\n|{{flag|Belize}}\n|{{Dts|21 October 2025}}<ref name=\":02\" />\n|}\n\n== Bilateral relations ==\n=== Africa ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%; margin:auto;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Country\n! style=\"width:12%;\"| Formal Relations Began\n!Notes\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Kenya}}||<!--Date started-->1970||See [[Kenya‚ÄìSri Lanka relations]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|South Africa}}||16 September 1994||See [[South Africa‚ÄìSri Lanka relations]]\n|}\n\n=== Americas ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%; margin:auto;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Country\n! style=\"width:12%;\"| Formal Relations Began\n!Notes\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Cuba}}||29 July 1959||See [[Cuba‚ÄìSri Lanka relations]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Mexico}}||<!--Date started-->19 April 1960||See [[Mexico‚ÄìSri Lanka relations]]\n\n* Mexico is accredited to Sri Lanka from its embassy in New Delhi, India, and maintains an honorary consulate in Colombo.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Inicio {{!}} Home|url=https://embamex.sre.gob.mx/india/|access-date=2021-11-15|website=embamex.sre.gob.mx}}</ref>\n* Sri Lanka is accredited to Mexico from its embassy in Washington, DC, United States, and maintains an honorary consulate in [[Mexico City]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Home|url=https://slembassyusa.org/new/|access-date=2021-11-15|website=slembassyusa.org|archive-date=19 June 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230619033326/https://slembassyusa.org/new/|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|United States}}||23 October 1948||See [[Sri Lanka‚ÄìUnited States relations]]\n[[File:Jayewardene presents elephant to Reagan.jpg|thumb|President [[J. R. Jayewardene|Jayewardene]] of Sri Lanka presents a baby elephant to President [[Ronald Reagan|Reagan]] and the American people in 1984]]\n\n*The US Embassy in Sri Lanka is located in Colombo, as are the US Agency for International Development offices and Public Affairs offices. IBB offices are located near [[Chilaw]], 75&nbsp;km north of Colombo.\n*[[Embassy of Sri Lanka, Washington, D.C.|Sri Lankan Embassy]] is located in Washington, DC.\n|}\n\n=== Asia ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%; margin:auto;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Country\n! style=\"width:12%;\"| Formal Relations Began\n!Notes\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Armenia}}||12 February 1992||See [[Foreign relations of Armenia]]\n\n* Armenia is accredited to Sri Lanka from its embassy in New Delhi, India.<ref name=\"mfa.am\">{{cite web| url=http://www.mfa.am/en/country-by-country/lk/ | title=Bilateral Relations | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171227231226/http://www.mfa.am/en/country-by-country/lk/ | archive-date=2017-12-27}}</ref> \n* Sri Lanka is accredited to Armenia from its embassy in Moscow, Russia.<ref name=\"mfa.am\"/> \n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Azerbaijan}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Foreign relations of Azerbaijan|Azerbaijan‚ÄìSri Lanka relations]]\n\n* Azerbaijan is accredited to Sri Lanka from its embassy in New Delhi, India.\n* Sri Lanka is accredited to Azerbaijan from its embassy in Tehran, Iran.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Bangladesh}}||1972||See [[Bangladesh ‚Äì Sri Lanka relations]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Bhutan}}||13 May 1987||\n\n* Diplomatic relations began in 1987.\n* The ambassador of the Sri Lankan High Commission in New Delhi is accredited to Bhutan.\n* The ambassador of the Bhutanese Embassy in Dhaka is accredited to Sri Lanka.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kuenselonline.com/modules.php?name=News&file=article&sid=10116|title=Topic: News in Bhutan other than Dzongkha and English.|work=KuenselOnline|access-date=21 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610234450/http://www.kuenselonline.com/modules.php?name=News&file=article&sid=10116|archive-date=10 June 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* Bhutan has an honorary consulate in Colombo.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|China}}||7 February 1957||See [[China‚ÄìSri Lanka relations]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|India}}||4 February 1948||See [[India‚ÄìSri Lanka relations]]\n\nBilateral relations between Sri Lanka and India have been generally friendly but were affected by the [[Sri Lankan civil war]] and by the failure of the [[Indian Peace Keeping Force]] during the civil war. India is Sri Lanka's only neighbour, separated by the [[Palk Strait]]. Both nations occupy a strategic position in South Asia and have sought to build a common security umbrella in the Indian Ocean.<ref name=\"SRI\">[https://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/735963.stm India's Sri Lankan scars]. BBC News (4 May 2000). Retrieved 12 November 2011.</ref>\n\nRelations between India and Sri Lanka relations have undergone a qualitative and quantitative transformation in the recent past. Political relations are close, trade and investments have increased dramatically, infrastructural linkages are constantly being augmented, defence collaboration has increased and there is a general, broad-based improvement across all sectors of bilateral cooperation. India was the first country to respond to Sri Lanka's request for assistance after the tsunami in December 2004. In July 2006, India evacuated 430 Sri Lankan nationals from Lebanon, first to Cyprus by Indian Navy ships and then to Delhi & Colombo by special Air India flights.\n\nThere exists a broad consensus within the Sri Lankan polity on the primacy of India in Sri Lanka's external relations matrix. Both major political parties in Sri Lanka, the Sri Lanka Freedom Party and the United Nationalist Party, have contributed to the rapid development of bilateral relations in the last ten years. Sri Lanka has supported India's candidature to the permanent membership of the UN Security\nCouncil.<ref>[http://mea.gov.in/foreignrelation/srilanka.htm Brief on India-Sri Lanka Relations], Ministry of External Affairs (BSM Division: Sri Lanka)</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Indonesia}}||6 August 1952||See [[Indonesia‚ÄìSri Lanka relations]]\n\n* Indonesia has an embassy in Colombo.\n* Sri Lanka has an embassy in Jakarta.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Iran}}||<!--Date started-->1961||See [[Iran‚ÄìSri Lanka relations]]\n\n[[Iran]] and Sri Lanka have had official diplomatic relations since 1961.<ref name=\"one\">[http://www.dailynews.lk/2009/08/05/news11.asp Sri Lanka ‚Äì Iran Bilateral Relations] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121011141256/http://www.dailynews.lk/2009/08/05/news11.asp |date=11 October 2012 }} Embassy of Sri Lanka in Iran</ref>\n\nDiplomatic relations between Iran and Sri Lanka (then known as Ceylon) began in 1961 via the Ceylonese embassy in [[Islamabad]], which was the closest Ceylon had to a presence on Iranian soil until the opening of the Tehran embassy office in 1990. Tehran set up its [[Colombo]] office in 1975.\n\nAfter [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]] became [[President of Iran]], Sri Lanka was the first country he visited on his inaugural Asian tour.<ref name=\"two\">[http://www.news.lk/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=15241&Itemid=52 The Group of 15 (G- 15)] [[Government of Sri Lanka]] ‚Äì 14 May 2010</ref> [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]] also made ties with Iran a priority after he ascended to office.<ref name=\"three\">[http://www.dailynews.lk/2010/02/20/news31.asp Sri Lanka, Iran mutual friends ‚Äì Minister] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121015012441/http://www.dailynews.lk/2010/02/20/news31.asp |date=15 October 2012 }} Daily News.lk ‚Äì 20 February 2010</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Iraq}}||22 February 1961||See [[Sri Lanka‚ÄìIraq relations]]\n\n* Sri Lanka has an embassy in [[Baghdad]]<ref>{{Cite web|title=Embassy of Sri Lanka in Iraq|url=http://www.slembirq.org/|access-date=2021-11-15|website=www.slembirq.org}}</ref>\n* Iraq has an embassy in [[Colombo]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mofamission.gov.iq/en/SriLank |title=Iraqi Embassy to Sri Lanka-Colombo |access-date=10 April 2019 |archive-date=10 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410152511/http://mofamission.gov.iq/en/SriLank |url-status=dead }}</ref>\nIraq was the largest buyer of Sri Lankan tea during the reign of [[Saddam Hussein]].  Ties between Sri Lanka and Iraq were disrupted during the [[Iraq War]]. However, in 2018 Iraq re-emerged as the largest buyer of Sri Lankan Tea.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.historyofceylontea.com/ceylon-publications/ceylon-tea-articles/iraq-emerges-to-be-the-no-1-buyer-of-sri-lankan-tea-in-2018.html|title = Iraq emerges to be the No. 1 buyer of Sri Lankan Tea in 2018 &#124; History of Ceylon Tea}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Israel}}||1 June 1956||See [[Israel‚ÄìSri Lanka relations]]\n\nSri Lanka has a close relationship with [[Israel]], and its military is a major user of Israeli weapons systems that include the [[IAI Kfir]] Fighter Jet, the [[Super Dvora Mk III]] class Patrol Vessel, and the [[Gabriel missile]]. In May 2011, the Israeli Minister of Agriculture visited Sri Lanka with an [[Agriculture in Israel|agro-business delegation]] to promote cooperation between the two countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jdslanka.org/2011/05/israeli-agriculture-minister-visits-sri.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405103500/http://www.jdslanka.org/2011/05/israeli-agriculture-minister-visits-sri.html|url-status=dead|title=Israeli agriculture minister visits Sri Lanka|archivedate=5 April 2012}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Japan}}||28 April 1952||See [[Japan ‚Äì Sri Lanka relations]]\n\nDuring the [[Second World War]], an air raid was carried out by Japan to bomb the city of Colombo in Sri Lanka. Later, relations between Japan and Sri Lanka became friendly, and they established official relations in 1952.\nJapan has an embassy in Colombo.<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.lk.emb-japan.go.jp/Index.html\n |title       = Embassy of Japan in Sri Lanka\n |access-date  = 18 July 2009\n |url-status     = dead\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090721233937/http://www.lk.emb-japan.go.jp/Index.html\n |archive-date = 21 July 2009\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> Sri Lanka has an embassy in Tokyo.<ref>{{cite web\n |url        = http://www.lankaembassy.jp/\n |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20051018040109/http://www.lankaembassy.jp/\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = 18 October 2005\n |title      = Embassy of Sri Lanka in Japan\n |access-date = 18 July 2009\n}}</ref> Sri Lankan President JR Jayawardene played a major role in re-admitting Japan to the world community at the [[San Francisco Conference]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Malaysia}}||October 1957||See [[Malaysia‚ÄìSri Lanka relations]]\n\nMalaysia has a high commission in Colombo,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kln.gov.my/web/lka_colombo/home|title=Official Website of High Commission of Malaysia, Colombo|publisher=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Malaysia]]|access-date=27 January 2014}}</ref> and Sri Lanka has a high commission in [[Kuala Lumpur]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slhc.com.my/index.php|title=Sri Lanka High Commission, Kuala Lumpur|publisher=High Commission of Sri Lanka in Malaysia|access-date=27 January 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140126043640/http://www.slhc.com.my/index.php|archive-date=26 January 2014}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Maldives}}||26 July 1965||See [[Maldives‚ÄìSri Lanka relations]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Nepal}}||<!--Date started-->1 July 1957||[[Foreign relations of Nepal]]\n\nNepal and Sri Lanka established diplomatic relations on 1 July 1957. Nepal opened an honorary consulate general in Colombo in 1975 and established its embassy in 1995. Sri Lanka has a residential embassy in Kathmandu since 1993. Around sixty thousand Sri Lankans visit Lumbini annually to pay homage to Gautam Buddha's birthplace [[Lumbini]], so Government of Sri Lanka has built a rest house and constructed a Buddhist monastery complex in [[Lumbini]].\n\nFollowing the [[April 2015 Nepal earthquake]], Sri Lanka was one of the first three countries to send medical and search-and-rescue teams to the country. The Sri Lanka Air Force|Aiorce sent flights of [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules|C-130 Hercules]] aircraft, and [[SriLankan Airlines]] sent [[Airbus A330]] aircraft, carrying Sri Lanka Army emergency teams.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/70317/sri-lanka-to-send-emergency-relief-to-nepal|title=Sri Lanka to send emergency relief to Nepal|date=25 April 2015}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Pakistan}}||May 1948||See [[Pakistan‚ÄìSri Lanka relations]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Palestine}}||April 1982||See [[Palestine‚ÄìSri Lanka relations]]\n*Palestine has very close ties to Sri Lanka.Sri Lanka has made monetary donations to Palestine on various occasions. Sri Lankan President Maithripala Sirisena also assured that Sri Lanka is committed to stand by the struggle for independence of the Palestinian people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/171231/news/president-expresses-support-for-palestine-275558.html|title = President expresses support for Palestine}}</ref> There is an embassy for the state of Palestine in Colombo.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mofa.pna.ps/ar/archives/4402 |title=ÿ≥ŸÅÿßÿ±ÿ© ÿØŸàŸÑÿ© ŸÅŸÑÿ≥ÿ∑ŸäŸÜ-ÿ¨ŸÖŸáŸàÿ±Ÿäÿ© ÿ≥ÿ±ŸäŸÑÿßŸÜŸÉÿß &#124; Ÿàÿ≤ÿßÿ±ÿ© ÿßŸÑÿÆÿßÿ±ÿ¨Ÿäÿ© ÿßŸÑŸÅŸÑÿ≥ÿ∑ŸäŸÜŸäÿ© |access-date=2 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161231081912/http://www.mofa.pna.ps/ar/archives/4402 |archive-date=31 December 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Philippines}}||17 April 1958||See [[Philippines‚ÄìSri Lanka relations]] \n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|South Korea}}||<!--Date started-->14 November 1977||\nsee [[South Korea‚ÄìSri Lanka relations]]\n\nDiplomatic relations between both nations were established on 14 November 1977. South Korean investments in Sri Lanka (cumulative total at the end of June 2014) total $731 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mofa.go.kr/ENG/countries/asiapacific/countries/20071018/1_24381.jsp?menu=m_30_10 |title=Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Republic of Korea-Asia Pacific |website=www.mofa.go.kr |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150904015758/http://www.mofa.go.kr/ENG/countries/asiapacific/countries/20071018/1_24381.jsp?menu=m_30_10 |archive-date=2015-09-04}}</ref> The Republic of Korea has an embassy in Colombo. Sri Lanka has an embassy in Seoul.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Turkey}}||September 1958||See [[Sri Lanka‚ÄìTurkey relations]]\n\n*Since 2012, Sri Lanka has an embassy in [[Ankara]].<ref name=\"mfa.gov.tr\">{{Cite web|title=From Rep. of Turkey Ministry of Foreign Affairs|url=https://www.mfa.gov.tr/turkey-sri-lanka-relations.en.mfa|access-date=2021-11-15|website=Republic of Turkey Ministry of Foreign Affairs}}</ref>\n*Since 2013, Turkey has an embassy in Colombo.<ref name=\"mfa.gov.tr\"/>\n|}\n\n=== Europe ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%; margin:auto;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Country\n! style=\"width:12%;\"| Formal Relations Began\n!Notes\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Croatia}}||14 February 1997||[[Foreign relations of Croatia]]\n\n*Sri Lanka recognised Croatia on 27 May 1992.<ref name=\"mvep.hr\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mvep.hr/en/foreign-politics/bilateral-relations/date-of-recognition-and-establishment-of-diplomatic-relations/|title=MVEP ‚Ä¢ Date of Recognition and Establishment of Diplomatic Relations}}</ref> \n*Both countries established diplomatic relations on 14 February 1997.<ref name=\"mvep.hr\"/> \n*Both countries have agreed on bilateral treaties in various fields.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mvep.hr/en/foreign-politics/bilateral-relations/overview-by-country/sri-lanka,130.html|title=MVEP ‚Ä¢ Overview of Bilateral Treaties of the Republic of Croatia by Country}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Cyprus}}||March 1981||\n* Cyprus is accredited to Sri Lanka by its High Commission in New Delhi, India<ref name=\"Home - MFA\">{{Cite web|title=Home - MFA|url=https://mfa.gov.cy/?OpenDocument|access-date=2021-11-15|website=mfa.gov.cy}}</ref> and an honorary consulate in Colombo.<ref name=\"Home - MFA\"/>\n*Sri Lanka is accredited to Cyprus from its embassy in Rome, Italy<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.srilankaembassyrome.org/en/the-embassy.html |title=The Embassy |access-date=26 January 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170208154853/http://www.srilankaembassyrome.org/en/the-embassy.html |archive-date=8 February 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and an honorary consulate in [[Larnaca]].<ref name=\"Home - MFA\"/>\n*Both countries have agreed on bilateral treaties in various fields.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.olc.gov.cy/olc/olc.nsf/all/936E47E4F95D5F31C22575D70033EFCF/$file/SRI%20LANKA.pdf?openelement |title=Sri Lanka |access-date=26 January 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202040106/http://www.olc.gov.cy/olc/olc.nsf/all/936E47E4F95D5F31C22575D70033EFCF/$file/SRI%20LANKA.pdf?openelement |archive-date=2 February 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \n*Both countries are full members of [[Commonwealth of Nations]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Czech Republic}}||28 December 1957 and 15 February 1993||\n\n* Historically, relations between the Czech Republic and Sri Lanka have been good, with foundations to build upon in strengthening bilateral cooperation.\n* There have been state visits by both sides.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2011/06/03/news22.asp |title=Sri Lanka News &#124; Online edition of Daily News - Lakehouse Newspapers |access-date=24 June 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609020246/http://www.dailynews.lk/2011/06/03/news22.asp |archive-date=9 June 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* The Czech Republic has a consulate in Colombo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://czech-republic.visahq.com/embassy/Sri-Lanka/|title=Embassy of Czech Republic in Sri Lanka|access-date=21 February 2015}}</ref>\n* In 2000 Czech Republic provided [[RM-70 multiple rocket launcher]]s for [[Sri Lanka Army]].<ref name=\"Sri Lanka Army Equipment\">[http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/sri-lanka/army-equipment.htm Sri Lanka Army Equipment]. globalsecurity.org. Retrieved 9 June 2013.</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Denmark}}||5 January 1953||See [[Denmark‚ÄìSri Lanka relations]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Estonia}}||31 January 1996||See [[Estonia‚ÄìSri Lanka relations]] \n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Germany}}||9 December 1953||See [[Germany‚ÄìSri Lanka relations]] \n* Germany has an embassy in Colombo.\n* Sri Lanka has an embassy in [[Berlin]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Greece}}||<!--Date started-->1957||\n\n*Both countries established diplomatic relations in 1957.<ref name=\"srilankaembassyrome.org\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.srilankaembassyrome.org/en/concurrent-accreditations/greece.html |title=Sri Lanka ‚Äì the Hellenic Republic: Bilateral Relations |access-date=26 January 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170221110715/http://www.srilankaembassyrome.org/en/concurrent-accreditations/greece.html |archive-date=21 February 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*Greece is accredited to Sri Lanka from its embassy in New Delhi, India.<ref name=\"mfa.gr\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mfa.gr/en/blog/greece-bilateral-relations/sri-lanka/|title = Greece's Bilateral Relations}}</ref> \n*Sri Lanka is accredited to Greece from its embassy in Rome, Italy.<ref name=\"srilankaembassyrome.org\"/><ref name=\"mfa.gr\"/>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Holy See}}||6 September 1975||See [[Holy See‚ÄìSri Lanka relations]]\n* Formal relations Began in 1978.\n* The Holy See has a nunciature in Colombo. Sri Lanka has an embassy in Rome.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Hungary}}||15 February 1959||See [[Hungary‚ÄìSri Lanka relations]]\n\n* Sri Lanka has an embassy in [[Vienna]], [[Austria]] that is accredited to Hungary.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.srilankaembassy.at/MainPage.htm \n |title=Embassy and Permanent Mission of Sri Lanka \n |publisher=Sri Lankan Embassy in Vienna \n |access-date=3 May 2009 \n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090504134755/http://www.srilankaembassy.at/MainPage.htm \n |archive-date=4 May 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n}} \n</ref> and has a consul in [[Budapest]]<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.kulugyminiszterium.hu/kum/hu/bal/Kulpolitikank/tb_konz_konf_2008/tb_konz_intezmeny_testulet/hun_tb_konz_lista.htm\n |title=List of honorary consuls in Hungary\n |publisher=Ministry for Foreign Affairs of the Republic of Hungary\n |language=hu\n |access-date=3 May 2009\n |archive-date=1 January 2009\n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090101165847/http://www.kulugyminiszterium.hu/kum/hu/bal/Kulpolitikank/tb_konz_konf_2008/tb_konz_intezmeny_testulet/hun_tb_konz_lista.htm\n |url-status=dead\n }}</ref>\n* Hungary maintains a consulate in Colombo.<ref>{{cite web\n |url        = http://www.slmfa.gov.lk/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=789&Itemid=84\n |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070610020959/http://www.slmfa.gov.lk//index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=789&Itemid=84\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = 10 June 2007\n |title      = Consulate of the Republic of Hungary\n |publisher  = Ministry for Foreign Affairs of the Republic of Hungary\n |access-date = 3 May 2009\n}}</ref>\n* Relations are low-keyed, but there are no outstanding issues. Hungary contributed to relief after the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake|2004 Indian Ocean tsunami]] and has since stepped up aid to Sri Lanka.<ref name=\"hunbilat\">{{cite web |title=Bilateral Relations (Sri Lanka) |url=https://bilateralnavigator.com/Hungary-SriLanka |access-date=3 May 2009 |publisher=Ministry for Foreign Affairs of the Republic of Hungary}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Romania}}||<!--Date started-->15 September 1957||See [[Romania‚ÄìSri Lanka relations]]\n\nThe Romanian Ambassador in New Delhi is concurrently accredited to Sri Lanka, and the Sri Lanka Mission in [[Warsaw]], Poland, is concurrently accredited to Romania.<ref name=\"srilankaembassy.com.pl\">{{cite web|url=http://www.srilankaembassy.com.pl/index.php/bilateral|title=Sri Lanka Poland Bilateral Relations|access-date=21 February 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205030919/http://www.srilankaembassy.com.pl/index.php/bilateral|archive-date=5 December 2014}}</ref> The President of Sri Lanka, Chandrika Bandaranaike Kumaratunga characterized relations between the two countries in 2003 as \"close and friendly\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2003/12/03/new21.html |title=Felicitations to Romania |access-date=24 June 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605024706/http://www.dailynews.lk/2003/12/03/new21.html |archive-date=5 June 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nDiplomatic relations between Sri Lanka and Romania were established on 15 September 1957. They werre initially maintained at [[Legation]] level but were raised to ambassadorial level in 1967. In 1963, Romania opened a commercial office in Colombo, which was upgraded to as embassy in 1976 with a [[charg√© d'affaires]]. The Romanian Mission in Colombo was closed in 1995 but reopened as a commercial office in 1998.\n\nIn 1978, the Sri Lankan minister of Foreign Affairs visited Romania.<ref name=\"srilankaembassy.com.pl\"/>\n\nRomania provided 32,000 euros worth of humanitarian aid to Sri Lanka after it was devastated by the December 2004 Indian Ocean tsunami in December 2004.<ref name=\"translate.google.com\">{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=ro&u=http://www.mae.ro/index.php%3Funde%3Ddoc%26id%3D5724&ei=0YEuS-W7N9CflAek162lBw&sa=X&oi=translate&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CBgQ7gEwBDgK&prev=/search%3Fq%3DValerica%2BEpure%2Band%2BLanka%26hl%3Den%26safe%3Doff%26client%3Dfirefox-a%26rls%3Dorg.mozilla:en-US:official%26sa%3DN%26start%3D10|title=Google Translate|access-date=21 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe ambassador designate of Sri Lanka in Bucharest was Clarence Felician Chinniah<ref name=\"translate.google.com\"/> until his death, in January 2009.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2009/01/10/news21.asp |title=Lankan Envoy to Poland passes away |access-date=24 June 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605024746/http://www.dailynews.lk/2009/01/10/news21.asp |archive-date=5 June 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asiantribune.com/?q=node/15115|title=Foreign Minister condoles the death of Sri Lankan envoy in Poland|access-date=21 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2009, Valerica Epure presented her credentials to President [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]] to become Ambassador-Designate of Romania to Sri Lanka.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adaderana.lk/news.php?nid=5285|title=Sri Lanka News-Adaderana-Truth First|access-date=21 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thaindian.com/newsportal/india-news/envoys-present-credentials-to-president-patil-4_100160772.html|title=Envoys present credentials to President Patil|work=Thaindian News|access-date=21 February 2015|archive-date=21 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150221171208/http://www.thaindian.com/newsportal/india-news/envoys-present-credentials-to-president-patil-4_100160772.html|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=HOME|url=http://sinhala.lankapuvath.lk/|access-date=2021-11-15|website=LankaPuvath|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.colombopage.com/archive_091/Sep1253197459CH.html|title=Sri Lanka : New ambassadors and high commissioner present credentials to Sri Lanka President|access-date=21 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2009, with the end of the civil war in Sri Lanka, 46 [[Sri Lankan Tamil]] refugees were sent to Romania to be processed for resettlement from [[Indonesia]] on their way to Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asiantribune.com/news/2009/12/30/sri-lankan-refugees-leave-indonesia-official|title=Sri Lankan refugees leave Indonesia: official|access-date=21 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nBilateral trade between Sri Lanka and Romania was valued at US$8.87&nbsp;million in 2007, up from US$7.9&nbsp;million in 2006.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2008/04/24/bus01.asp |title=Romanian market still untapped |access-date=24 June 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605023650/http://www.dailynews.lk/2008/04/24/bus01.asp |archive-date=5 June 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Efforts have been made to expand trade in [[Ceylon tea]] to Romania.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2005/12/29/bus07.htm |title=Tea Board taps Romanian and Serbian tea markets |access-date=24 June 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605024632/http://www.dailynews.lk/2005/12/29/bus07.htm |archive-date=5 June 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2009, the chairman and CEO of the Sri Lanka Export Development Board, Anil Koswatte, singled out Romania as country to which exports could be increased.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2009/08/03/bus01.asp |title=Golden opportunity to expand exports |access-date=24 June 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605024713/http://www.dailynews.lk/2009/08/03/bus01.asp |archive-date=5 June 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Russia}}||19 February 1957||See [[Russia‚ÄìSri Lanka relations]]\n\n[[File:Rajapaksa and Medvedev at St Petersburg Economic Forum.jpeg|thumb|President [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]] with Russian President [[Dmitry Medvedev]], at [[St. Petersburg International Economic Forum|St. Petersburg Economic Forum]], in June 2011.]]\n*During the war between the Sri Lanka Armed Forces and the Tamil Tigers, Russia helped the Sri Lankese government by providing education on battlefield tactics to the Sri Lanka Army.\n*Russia has an embassy in Colombo. Sri Lanka has an [[Embassy of Sri Lanka in Moscow|embassy]] in Moscow.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Serbia}}||14 October 1957||\n\n*Both countries established diplomatic relations in 1956.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mfa.gov.rs/en/foreign-policy/bilateral-issues/96-bilateral-issues/12366-sri-lanka |title=Sri Lanka |website=www.mfa.gov.rs |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161231080118/http://www.mfa.gov.rs/en/foreign-policy/bilateral-issues/96-bilateral-issues/12366-sri-lanka |archive-date=2016-12-31}}</ref> \n*A number of bilateral agreements in various fields have been concluded and are in force between both countries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mfa.gov.rs/en/images/stories/bilaterala_ugovori/SRI%20LANKA.doc |title=SRI LANKA |access-date=30 December 2016 |archive-date=31 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161231080543/http://www.mfa.gov.rs/en/images/stories/bilaterala_ugovori/SRI%20LANKA.doc |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Spain}}||10 July 1955||See [[Spain‚ÄìSri Lanka relations]]\n* Spain is accredited to Sri Lanka from its embassy in New Delhi, India. \n* Sri Lanka is accredited to Spain from its embassy in Paris, France.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Switzerland}}||23 January 1956||See [[Sri Lanka‚ÄìSwitzerland relations]]\n\nIn the 1980s, political relations between Switzerland and Sri Lanka intensified, with many Sri Lankan Tamils fleeing from the Sri Lankan civil war to find asylum in Switzerland.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|United Kingdom}}||4 February 1948||See [[Sri Lanka‚ÄìUnited Kingdom relations]]\n\n[[Foreign relations of the United Kingdom|Diplomatic relations with the United Kingdom]] were established on 22 October 1946.\n*Sri Lanka maintains a [[High Commission of Sri Lanka, London|high commission]] in London.\n*The United Kingdom is accredited to Sri Lanka through its high commission in [[Colombo]].<ref>{{cite web|title=British High Commission Colombo|work=GOV.UK|url=https://www.gov.uk/world/organisations/british-high-commission-colombo|access-date=7 July 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240707052142/https://www.gov.uk/world/organisations/british-high-commission-colombo|archive-date=7 July 2024|url-status=live}}</ref>\nThe UK governed [[British Ceylon|Sri Lanka]] from 1802 to 1948, until it achieved full independence as [[Dominion of Ceylon|Ceylon]].\n\nBoth countries share common membership of the [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] and the [[World Trade Organization]]. Bilaterally the two countries have an Investment Agreement.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://investmentpolicy.unctad.org/international-investment-agreements/treaties/bilateral-investment-treaties/2964/sri-lanka---united-kingdom-bit-1980-|title=Sri Lanka - United Kingdom BIT (1980)|website=UN Trade and Development|access-date=16 June 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230531223506/https://investmentpolicy.unctad.org/international-investment-agreements/treaties/bilateral-investment-treaties/2964/sri-lanka---united-kingdom-bit-1980-|archive-date=31 May 2023|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|}\n\n=== Oceania ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%; margin:auto;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Country\n! style=\"width:12%;\"| Formal Relations Began\n!Notes\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Australia}}||4 February 1948||See [[Australia‚ÄìSri Lanka relations]]\n\n*Australia has a High Commission in Colombo.\n*Sri Lanka has a ([[High Commission of Sri Lanka in Canberra|High Commission]]) in [[Canberra]] and five consulates-general in [[Adelaide]], [[Brisbane]], [[Melbourne]], [[Perth]] and Sydney.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{anchor|New Zealand}}{{flag|New Zealand}}||14 December 1955||See [[Foreign relations of New Zealand]]\n\n[[New Zealand]] and Sri Lanka have a strong relationship since the 1800s. New Zealand has longstanding Commonwealth, migrant and sporting ties with Sri Lanka.\n\n* New Zealand has a High Commission in Colombo.\n* Sri Lanka is accredited to New Zealand from its high commission in Canberra, Australia.\n\nNew Zealand visits to Sri Lanka:\n*Prime Minister John Key and Minister of Foreign Affairs Hon Murray McCully visited Sri Lanka for the 23rd [[Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting 2013]]. \n*Hon Murray McCully, Minister of Foreign Affairs, June, August 2013\n*Sri Lankan Parliamentary Delegation attending the Commonwealth Parliamentary Association Conference, October 1998\n*Agriculture, Lands & Forestry Minister Jayaratne, May 1996<ref name=\"test\">{{cite web| url=http://www.mfat.govt.nz/Countries/Asia-South-and-Southeast/Sri-Lanka.php| title=Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka | publisher=Ministry of Foreign Affairs, New Zealand | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141103224735/http://www.mfat.govt.nz/Countries/Asia-South-and-Southeast/Sri-Lanka.php | archive-date=2014-11-03}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[List of diplomatic missions in Sri Lanka]]\n* [[List of diplomatic missions of Sri Lanka]]\n* [[Sri Lanka and the Non-Aligned Movement]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Copper, J. F. \"China and Sri-Lanka: Old Friendship Renewed.\" ''Asia Quarterly'' 2 (1975): 101-110.\n* H√∂glund, Kristine, and Isak Svensson. \"Mediating between tigers and lions: Norwegian peace diplomacy in Sri Lanka's civil war.\" ''Contemporary South Asia'' 17.2 (2009): 175-191.\n* Peebles, Patrick. ''The History of Sri Lanka'' (Greenwood, 2005)\n* Suryanarayan, V, \"Sri Lanka's policy towards China: Legacy of the past and prospects for the future.\" ''China Report'' 30.2 (1994): 203-21\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140908140458/http://www.mea.gov.lk/ Ministry of External Affairs of Sri Lanka]\n* [http://www.sundaytimes.lk/090830/FinancialTimes/ft09.html Fallacy and the Reality of IMF Standby Arrangement for Sri Lanka] by ''[[The Sunday Times]]''\n\n{{Foreign relations of the Commonwealth of Nations}}\n{{Foreign relations of the Sri Lanka |expanded=Bilateral}}\n{{Politics of Sri Lanka navbox}}\n{{Asia in topic|Foreign relations of}}\n\n[[Category:Foreign relations of Sri Lanka| ]]\n[[Category:Sri Lanka and the Commonwealth of Nations]]"